goals.question: What is the distribution of daily returns?
goals.rationale: This visualization helps to understand the volatility of the stock. If the distribution is normal, it means the stock is stable and predictable. If the distribution is skewed, it means the stock is volatile and unpredictable.

goals.question: What is the correlation between open and close prices?
goals.visualization: Scatter plot of open vs close
goals.rationale: This visualization helps to understand the relationship between the opening and closing prices. If the points are clustered around a line, it means there is a strong correlation between the two variables. If the points are scattered, it means there is no correlation.

goals.question: What is the trend of the stock over time?
goals.visualization: Line chart of date vs adjclose
goals.rationale: This visualization helps to understand the overall trend of the stock. If the line is going up, it means the stock is increasing in value over time. If the line is going down, it means the stock is decreasing in value over time.

goals.question: What is the average daily return of the stock?
goals.rationale: This visualization helps to understand the average daily return of the stock. If the bar is high, it means the stock has a high average daily return. If the bar is low, it means the stock has a low average daily return.

goals.question: What is the volume of the stock over time?
goals.visualization: Line chart of date vs volume
goals.rationale: This visualization helps to understand the trading volume of the stock over time. If the line is going up, it means the stock is being traded more frequently. If the line is going down, it means the stock is being traded less frequently.

import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    sns.histplot(data['daily_return'], kde=True)
    plt.title('What is the distribution of daily returns?', wrap=True)
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
chart.show()

import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], errors='ignore')
    sns.lineplot(x='date', y='adjclose', data=data)
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.title('What is the trend of the stock over time?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
chart.show()

import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], errors='ignore')
    sns.barplot(x='date', y='average_daily_return', data=data)
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    plt.axhline(data['average_daily_return'].mean(), color='red', linestyle='--', label=f"Mean: {data['average_daily_return'].mean():.2f}")
    plt.legend()
    plt.title("What is the average daily return of the stock?", wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
chart.show()
